excerpt: This restored castle originally completed in 1612 features artifacts & exhibits on the Edo Period.
detail_description: Nagoya Castle, originally built in the 17th century and reconstructed in 1959, offers a glimpse into Japan's history during the Edo Period. The castle features artifacts, costumes, weaponry, and artwork that tell the story of ancient Japan. One of its famous features is the shachi-hoko, a creature with the head of a tiger and body of a fish. Surrounding the castle is Ninomaru-en garden known for its picturesque teahouses.
name: Nagoya Castle
address: 1-1 Honmaru, Naka Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 460-0031, Japan

excerpt: This revered shrine surrounded by cypress trees contains a sacred sword & has artifacts on display.
detail_description: Atsuta Jingu, a revered shrine located in Nagoya, is known for housing the sacred Kusanagi-no Tsurugi sword and hosting the annual Atsuta-sai Festival. The shrine attracts around 6.5 million visitors annually and is surrounded by picturesque cypress trees. Its Treasure Hall showcases over 4,000 ancient household articles and materials, offering insight into the deep-rooted beliefs associated with the shrine.
name: Atsuta-jingu Shrine
address: 1 Chome-1-1 Jingu, Atsuta Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 456-8585, Japan

excerpt: Textile & car machinery, plus exhibits on the carmaker's origins, on display in a former factory.
detail_description: The Toyota Commemorative Museum of Industry and Technology in Nagoya is a must-visit for car enthusiasts. Housed in a former factory, the museum showcases the origins of the carmaker and features exhibits on textile and car machinery. Visitors can explore a wide collection of classic and modern cars from popular brands worldwide, providing insight into the development of the automotive industry.
name: Toyota Commemorative Museum of Industry and Technology
address: 4 Chome-1-35 Noritakeshinmachi, Nishi Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 451-0051, Japan

excerpt: This museum displays 35+ railway vehicles, including steam locomotives & bullet-train cars.
detail_description: SCMaglev and Railway Park is a museum that showcases over 35 railway vehicles, including steam locomotives and bullet-train cars. The park was built with the concept of being a place of dreams and memories, offering visitors the chance to view 38 actual trains up close. These include examples from different eras, such as the 1913 steam locomotive, passenger trains used after the war, and intergenerational Bullet Trains.
name: SCMaglev and Railway Park
address: 3 Chome-2-2 Kinjofuto, Minato Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 455-0848, Japan

excerpt: Science museum with a large planetarium, as well as exhibits on weather, biology & electricity.
detail_description: Nagoya City Science Museum, situated in the northern part of Shirakawa Park, is a seven-story building housing a massive metal sphere that hosts the world's largest planetarium. The museum offers interactive experiences such as simulating the climate of the South Pole at -32°C. While primarily aimed at children and teenagers, it also appeals to adults with its diverse exhibits on weather, biology, and electricity. Although most descriptions are in Japanese, English translations are available for some displays.
name: Nagoya City Science Museum
address: Japan, 〒460-0008 Aichi, Nagoya, Naka Ward, Sakae, 2 Chome−17−1, 芸術と科学の杜・白川公園内

excerpt: Modern aquarium with many species, including whales, a dolphin show & food & drink concessions.
detail_description: The Port of Nagoya Public Aquarium is a modern facility that offers a diverse range of marine species, including whales and dolphins. Visitors can enjoy captivating animal performances in the massive 3,000-seater main pool. The aquarium's Journey to the Antarctic exhibition allows guests to explore the icy plains of one of Earth's coldest places. It is a popular destination for families with kids and marine life enthusiasts from around the globe.
name: Port Of Nagoya Public Aquarium
address: 1-3 Minatomachi, Minato Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 455-0033, Japan

excerpt: Museum tracing Japanese history through art & cultural artifacts, with quiet gardens on site.
detail_description: The Tokugawa Art Museum, situated in the historic Nagoya's Tokugawa Park, is a renowned institution showcasing an extensive collection of artifacts and cultural relics from the influential Tokugawa family. With over 10,000 pieces including national treasures such as samurai armor and Noh theater artifacts, it offers a fascinating insight into Japanese history and culture. The museum also provides access to the Hosa Bunko library which houses rare books from generations of the Owari Tokugawa family.
name: Tokugawa Art Museum
address: 1017 Tokugawacho, Higashi Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 461-0023, Japan

excerpt: This attraction has a zoo with 125+ species, a greenhouse with gardens & an amusement park.
detail_description: Higashiyama Zoo and Botanical Gardens, located in Nagoya, is a popular tourist spot offering a diverse range of attractions. The zoo boasts over 125 species of mammals, 70 species of reptiles, and more than 86 species of birds. Adjacent to the zoo is the city's Botanical Gardens featuring an extensive greenhouse with over 7,000 varieties of plants from different environments such as desert and jungle.
name: Higashiyama Zoo and Botanical Gardens
address: 3 Chome-７０ Higashiyama Motomachi, Chikusa Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 464-0804, Japan

excerpt: Museum, gardens & shops on the former factory grounds of a prominent Japanese ceramics company.
detail_description: Noritake Garden is a historical site located on the former grounds of a renowned Japanese ceramics company, established in 1904. The garden features well-preserved relics such as old kilns and offers a gallery showcasing the rich history of ceramics production. Visitors can also engage in hands-on activities at the Craft Centre & Museum, where they can create and glaze their own ceramic pieces. Additionally, there is a shop offering various ceramic items for purchase as souvenirs.
name: Noritake Garden
address: 3 Chome-1-36 Noritakeshinmachi, Nishi Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 451-8501, Japan

excerpt: Colorful theme park with rides & games for children, a factory tour & block-building activities.
detail_description: Legoland Japan Resort, opened in 2017, is a vibrant and family-oriented theme park offering an array of rides and games tailored for children. The park also features a fascinating factory tour and engaging block-building activities. Situated near Kinjofuto Station, it has quickly become one of Nagoya's top attractions. While primarily designed for kids, the park offers plenty to captivate adults as well, including impressive Lego models and diverse themed areas inspired by the Lego universe.
name: Legoland Japan
address: LEGOLAND Japan Limited, 1 Kinjoufutou, 2 Chome-2 Kinjofuto, Minato Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 455-8605, Japan

excerpt: Rebuilt Buddhist temple founded in the 14th century, with a library of important classical works.
detail_description: Osu Kannon is a stunning Buddhist temple situated at the end of Osu Shopping Arcade in downtown Nagoya. Although its buildings are modern due to being rebuilt after destruction in 1945, it still holds historical significance as it was originally constructed in 1333 and relocated to its current location in 1612. The temple is dedicated to Kannon, the Buddhist Goddess of mercy and compassion.
name: Osu Kannon (Kitanosan Shinpuku-ji Hoshoin)
address: 2 Chome-21-47 Osu, Naka Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 460-0011, Japan

excerpt: Centuries-old merchant quarter with Buddhist temples & a central arcade of boutiques & restaurants.
detail_description: Osu Shōtengai Shopping District, with a history of over 400 years, is a vibrant and historic merchant quarter in Nagoya. It's home to over 1,200 businesses including Buddhist temples, food stalls, clothing shops, cafes, restaurants, bars and more. The area offers a mix of traditional and contemporary culture with hidden surprises waiting to be discovered.
name: Osu Shotengai Shopping Street
address: 3 Chome Osu, Naka Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 460-0011, Japan

excerpt: Tranquil Japanese-style garden with a pathway along streams & ponds, plus a tea ceremony house.
detail_description: Shirotori Garden is a serene Japanese-style garden in Nagoya, offering a tranquil escape from the city. Spanning 3.7 hectares, it's designed to reflect the natural beauty and geography of the surrounding area. The main pond symbolizes Ise Bay, while the stream represents the Kiso River and a hill mimics Mount Ontake.
name: Shirotori Garden
address: 2-5 Atsuta Nishimachi, Atsuta Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 456-0036, Japan

excerpt: Oval-shaped complex with a glass ceiling, offering multiple retail shops, eateries & a bus terminal.
detail_description: Oasis 21 is a unique oval-shaped complex in Nagoya, featuring a glass ceiling and housing various retail shops, eateries, and a bus terminal. The highlight of this shopping center is its incredible rooftop garden designed like an oval UFO, offering stunning views of Nagoya and the iconic Nagoya TV Tower. The rooftop plaza features a large pond that cools the shopping center below and provides picturesque cityscapes, especially at night.
name: Oasis 21
address: 1 Chome-11-1 Higashisakura, Higashi Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 461-0005, Japan

excerpt: Sakae is an energetic downtown retail and entertainment district packed with boutiques and modern malls like Sunshine Sakae, topped by the Sky Boat Ferris wheel. Within Shirakawa Park, there’s a popular planetarium at the City Science Museum and surrealist paintings by Kansuke Yamamoto in the striking City Art Museum. Commuters fill busy noodle bars, and neon-lit high-rise buildings house multiple pubs and clubs.
detail_description: Sakae is a bustling urban hub in downtown Nagoya, offering a vibrant mix of retail therapy and entertainment. Visitors can explore modern malls like Sunshine Sakae and enjoy a ride on the Sky Boat Ferris wheel. The district also boasts cultural attractions such as the City Science Museum with its popular planetarium and the City Art Museum showcasing surrealist paintings by Kansuke Yamamoto. Noodle bars and lively pubs cater to both locals and commuters, adding to the area's dynamic atmosphere.
name: Sakae
address: Naka Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 460-0008, Japan

excerpt: Museum tracing the history of automobiles, with chronological displays of rare & classic cars.
detail_description: The Toyota Automobile Museum is a fascinating destination for car enthusiasts, showcasing the evolution of automobiles through rare and classic cars. The exhibition hall provides a comprehensive narrative of Toyota's entrepreneurial journey, reflecting the historical transformation of the country with products from different eras. Located near the 2005 Aichi World Expo venue, the museum features antique cars from America, Europe, and Japan spanning over a century.
name: Toyota Automobile Museum
address: 41-100 Yokomichi, Nagakute, Aichi 480-1118, Japan

excerpt: Leafy park flanked by city streets, with a manmade river, fountains, orchid garden & TV tower.
detail_description: Hisaya Ōdōri Park, located at the heart of Nagoya in Sakae, is a picturesque urban oasis surrounded by city streets. The park features a manmade river, fountains, an orchid garden, and the iconic Chubu Electric Power MIRAI TOWER. Visitors can enjoy stunning views from the 90-meter high Sky Deck and 100-meter high Sky Balcony. The park hosts cultural events, exhibitions, and seasonal festivals throughout the year.
name: Hisaya Ōdōri Park
address: 3 Chome-ほか Marunouchi, Naka Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 460-0002, Japan

excerpt: Nagoya, capital of Japan’s Aichi Prefecture, is a manufacturing and shipping hub in central Honshu. The city’s Naka ward is home to museums and pachinko (gambling machine) parlors. Naka also includes the Sakae entertainment district, with attractions like the Sky-Boat Ferris wheel, which is attached to a mall. In northern Naka is Nagoya Castle, a partly reconstructed 1612 royal home displaying Edo-era artifacts.
detail_description: Nagoya, the capital of Japan's Aichi Prefecture, is a bustling city known for its manufacturing and shipping industries. The Naka ward is a vibrant area with museums, pachinko parlors, and the Sakae entertainment district featuring attractions like the Sky-Boat Ferris wheel. Visitors can explore Nagoya Castle in northern Naka, which showcases Edo-era artifacts and offers a glimpse into royal history.
name: Nagoya
address: Aichi, Japan

detail_description: Ghibli Park, located on the outskirts of Nagoya, is a newly opened theme park dedicated to the iconic movies and animated works of Studio Ghibli. It is the world's first park of its kind and has quickly become a popular attraction since its late 2022 opening. Visitors can explore attractions like Ghibli's Grand Warehouse, which are now accessible to overseas visitors.
name: Ghibli Park
address: 乙１５３３−１, Ibaragabasama, Nagakute, Aichi 480-1342, Japan

excerpt: Open-air observation promenade offering 360-degree views of the city, plus a small bar with food.
detail_description: The Sky Promenade, situated in Midland Square, boasts the title of Japan's tallest observation deck. Perched on the 44th to 46th floors, this open-air observation promenade offers breathtaking 360-degree views of Nagoya. Visitors can savor panoramic vistas of the city and its surroundings. Additionally, there are sky view restaurants accessible through winding passages, adding to the overall experience.
name: Sky Promenade
address: 4 Chome-7-1 Meieki, Nakamura Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 450-0002, Japan

excerpt: Popular mall in a tower atop a train station with many shops & restaurants, plus hotels.
detail_description: JR Central Towers is a prominent complex located above the JR Nagoya Station in Japan. Comprising the 51-storey JR Central Office Towers and the 53-storey JR Central Hotel Tower, it serves as a bustling transport hub and features an array of shops, restaurants, and even a public observatory called Panorama House offering breathtaking city views. The site also hosts the annual Nagoya festival (matsuri) during autumn.
name: JR Central Towers
address: 1 Chome-1-4 Meieki, Nakamura Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 450-6001, Japan

excerpt: Known for its cherry blossom forest, this historic park also has ponds, tennis courts & gardens.
detail_description: Tsuruma Park, located near JR Tsurumai Station, is a historic public park established in 1909 and celebrated as one of Japan's top spots for cherry blossom viewing. The park features a beautiful cherry blossom forest, ponds, tennis courts, and gardens. It offers visitors the chance to experience the cherished Japanese tradition of Hanami, or Cherry Blossom Viewing party.
name: Tsuruma Park
address: 1 Tsurumai, Showa Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 466-0064, Japan

excerpt: This mall inside an office tower features upscale fashion & jewelry stores, plus dining & a cinema.
detail_description: Midland Square is a shopping complex located within the Toyota Mainichi Building, the tallest skyscraper in Nagoya at 247 meters high. The mall houses luxury brand boutiques like Cartier, Dior, and Louis Vuitton, as well as Lexus and Toyota showrooms. Additionally, it features a cinema on the 5th floor and restaurants on the 41st and 42nd floors.
name: Midland Square
address: 4 Chome-7-1 Meieki, Nakamura Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 450-0002, Japan

excerpt: Arimatsu is a town in Aichi Prefecture, Japan. It houses the Arimatsu Station of the Meitetsu-Nagoya Line, roughly 11 kilometres southeast of downtown Nagoya. The town merged into Nagoya on 1 December 1964, and became a part of Midori-ku, Nagoya. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Arimatsu, situated in Aichi Prefecture, Japan, is home to the Arimatsu Station of the Meitetsu-Nagoya Line. This town merged into Nagoya in 1964 and is now part of Midori-ku. The post town of Arimatsu, positioned on the Tokaido Highway, was recognized as a National Important Preservation District for Groups of Historic Buildings in 2016.
name: Arimatsu
address: Midori Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 458-0924, Japan

detail_description: Yanagibashi Central Market is a historic market spanning 13000 square meters, with a legacy of about 100 years. It boasts over 300 stores offering an array of locally caught fish and seafood products. This bustling market provides an authentic glimpse into the daily lives of Nagoya locals as they shop for fresh produce, meat, and seafood. Visitors can witness the vibrant atmosphere as vendors break down massive tuna and sell various live seafood.
name: Yanagibashi Central Market
address: 4 Chome-15-2 Meieki, Nakamura Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 450-0002, Japan

excerpt: Large & vibrant port featuring a public aquarium, amusement park, shopping mall & museums.
detail_description: Nagoya Port, located in Ise Bay, is not only a bustling harbor but also a popular tourist destination. It features the impressive Port of Nagoya Public Aquarium, which houses a diverse collection of native and exotic marine life and hosts entertaining dolphin shows. The port also offers sightseeing cruises, an amusement park, shopping mall, and museums for visitors to enjoy. Additionally, it is one of Japan's major ports for international trade alongside offering seasonal events like the Christmas Fire Festival.
name: Nagoya Port
address: 1-3 Minatomachi, Minato Ward, Nagoya, Aichi, Japan

excerpt: The world's largest train station by square feet offers shops, eateries, lodging & office space.
detail_description: Nagoya Station is the world's largest train station, offering a wide array of amenities such as shops, eateries, lodging, and office space. The station is home to various establishments like Ebizukushi and Arimatsu Shibori Bag. Additionally, located near Nagoya Station in Nagoya City, Ushiwaka is a well-established yakiniku restaurant that has been serving locals and visitors for over 40 years.
name: Nagoya Station
address: 1 Chome-1-4 Meieki, Nakamura Ward, Nagoya, Aichi, Japan

excerpt: Airy, modern museum with permanent & temporary exhibitions of contemporary art in various mediums.
detail_description: Nagoya City Art Museum is a modern and airy museum located in Shirakawa Park, just across from the Nagoya City Science Museum. Designed by renowned architect Kisho Kurokawa, the museum itself is considered a work of art. It houses both permanent and temporary exhibitions featuring contemporary art in various mediums from around the world, including Mexican Renaissance, Ecole de Paris, and local Japanese art.
name: Nagoya City Art Museum
address: Japan, 〒460-0008 Aichi, Nagoya, Naka Ward, Sakae, 2 Chome−17−25, 芸術と科学の杜・白川公園内

excerpt: The craft of traditional Japanese tie-dying is showcased via demos & displays in an intimate space.
detail_description: Located in Nagoya, the Arimatsu Narumi Shibori Tie-Dyeing Museum offers an intimate space to showcase the traditional Japanese tie-dying craft through demonstrations and displays. The museum provides a comprehensive insight into the art of shibori or tie-dyeing, featuring galleries that narrate its history and local artisans demonstrating the intricate process of creating these pieces.
name: Arimatsu Narumi Shibori Tie-Dyeing Museum
address: 絞会館, 3008 Arimatsu, Midori Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 458-0924, Japan

excerpt: Traditional Edo-style pedestrianized street for cuisine such as katsu & tempura, plus souvenirs.
detail_description: Kinshachi Yokocho is a traditional Edo-style pedestrianized street located near the main gate of Nagoya Castle. It offers a variety of restaurants serving Nagoya cuisine, such as Miso Nikomi Udon and Miso Katsu. The area represents the castle town of the Edo period, providing an opportunity to immerse in history and culture while enjoying local dishes and snacks. Visitors can stroll through shops, taste different local foods, and take a break after exploring the castle.
name: Kinshachi Yokocho
address: Japan, 〒460-0001 Aichi, 義直/名古屋市中区三の丸1丁目2番3～5 宗春/名古屋市中区二の丸1番2・3号

detail_description: Nagoya Port, located in the southern part of the city, has transformed into a vibrant leisure district with plenty of attractions for families. The port area is home to the Nagoya Aquarium, Sea Train Land amusement park, and the Fuji Antarctic museum, making it an ideal destination for travelers with kids. With a variety of entertainment options available, visitors can enjoy a fun-filled day exploring the diverse offerings at Nagoya Port.
name: Nagoya Port
address: Japan

excerpt: Stately cultural & administrative center with Western architecture, formerly a court building.
detail_description: The Nagoya City Archives and Museum is a grand old building with a mix of Chinese, Japanese, and Western architectural styles. Once serving as the Nagoya municipal building, it has been repurposed into a museum showcasing the history and natural resources of Nagoya.
name: Nagoya City Archives and Museum
address: 1 Chome-3 Shirakabe, Higashi Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 461-0011, Japan

excerpt: Tranquil temple containing Nobuhide's tomb, a bamboo grove & a towering green Buddha statue.
detail_description: Tōgan-ji Temple, located in the Motoyama area, is a serene and historic site dating back to the sixteenth century. It is renowned for its remarkable 15-meter tall dark-green Buddha statue, known as Daibutu. Visitors flock to this small temple not only to admire the towering statue but also to touch a large wooden block believed to possess healing and purifying powers. The temple holds significant ties to India, with one of its high priests completing studies there.
name: Tōgan-ji Temple
address: 2 Chome-16 Yotsuyatori, Chikusa Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 464-0819, Japan

excerpt: Collection of mostly modern works by icons such as Picasso & Matisse, plus Japanese artists.
detail_description: The Aichi Prefectural Museum of Art, located in Nagoya, Japan, is a renowned art museum featuring a diverse collection of modern paintings and sculptures. The museum showcases works by iconic international artists such as Picasso, Matisse, Klimt, Ernst, and Bonnard alongside precious pieces by Japanese artists like Takahashi and Yokoyama. Visitors can explore limited-edition prints, historic drawings, calligraphy displays, and temporary exhibitions on various artists and topical events.
name: Aichi Prefectural Museum Of Art
address: 1 Chome-13-2 Higashisakura, Higashi Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 461-0005, Japan

excerpt: Verdant city park known for its modern sculptures & fountains, plus science & art museums.
detail_description: Shirakawa Park, located in Nagoya, is a lush city park featuring modern sculptures and fountains. It is adjacent to the Nagoya City Science Museum and houses the Nagoya City Art Museum. The park is a popular gathering spot with its large fountains, sun clock, and contemporary art installations. One of the main attractions within the park is the Guinness-certified world's largest planetarium at the Nagoya Science Museum.
name: Shirakawa Park
address: 2 Chome-17 Sakae, Naka Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 460-0008, Japan

detail_description: The Meitetsu Department Store Main Store is a classic Nagoya establishment situated directly above Nagoya Station, just 28 minutes from Central Airport. It's known for its 'Massage' and 'Men's Hall', offering a wide range of men's products. The store is a hub for fashion and upscale boutiques, while the 9th floor food court serves authentic Nagoya cuisine like 'Mei Yu pork chops' and 'Nagoya specialty eel rice'.
name: Meitetsu Department Store Main Store
address: 1 Chome-2-1 Meieki, Nakamura Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 450-0002, Japan

excerpt: Agricultural park featuring orchards, cherry blossoms, gardens & a greenhouse, plus shops & dining.
detail_description: Nestled at the base of Nagoya's highest mountain, Mt. Higashiya, Togokusan Fruits Park is a delightful agricultural park offering a range of attractions. Visitors can explore 15 orchards featuring various fruits and tropical delights, as well as a fruit house showcasing an array of fruits. The park also boasts a Japanese garden, seasonal flower beds, and dining options.
name: Togokusan Fruits Park
address: Togoku-2110 Kamishidami, Moriyama Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 463-0001, Japan

excerpt: Busy mall, home to the Sky-Boat Ferris wheel, with clothing & electronics stores & casual dining.
detail_description: Sunshine Sakae is a bustling shopping and entertainment complex in Nagoya, Japan. It's a popular spot for locals and tourists alike, offering a wide range of international brands, casual dining options, and entertainment. One of its standout features is the Sky-Boat Ferris wheel, which is illuminated with thousands of LED lights at night. This unique attraction hangs off the side of the shopping center and provides stunning views of the Nagoya skyline from its perspex capsules.
name: Sunshine Sakae
address: 3 Chome-24-4 Nishiki, Naka Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 460-0003, Japan

excerpt: Showa-inspired area with a mix of fashionable shops & enduring stores, plus trendy eateries & bars.
detail_description: Endo-ji Shotengai Shopping Street is a charming area in Nishi Ward, Nagoya, known for its mix of fashionable shops, enduring stores, trendy eateries, and bars. It's also famous for its concentration of confectionery manufacturers and wholesalers. The area boasts historical resources like Shikenmichi Road and Mino Road and is considered the birthplace of modern industries.
name: Endo-ji Shotengai Shopping Street
address: 1 Chome-6-16 Nagono, Nishi Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 451-0042, Japan

detail_description: The Noritake Museum and Craft Center offers a fascinating look into the history of Japanese porcelain manufacturing. Housed in the former Noritake factory, the complex includes a museum showcasing a wide range of ceramics products created by Noritake over the years. Visitors can explore the sprawling grounds, which feature remnants of ancient red kilns and beautifully landscaped gardens. The museum also boasts an impressive collection that includes pieces designed by renowned architect Frank Lloyd Wright.
name: Noritake Museum and Craft Center
address: 3 Chome-1-36 Noritakeshinmachi, Nishi Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 451-8501, Japan

excerpt: 4th-floor museum with design objects from the 1920s to the present, plus a creative workshop.
detail_description: Located in Nagoya, the International Design Centre Nagoya is situated in a historical district known for its Edo merchant trade roots. The center is housed within the Nadya Park complex and features a museum on the fourth floor showcasing design objects from the 1920s to present, as well as a creative workshop. Visitors can explore design touchstones from various eras and notable designers, tracing the evolution of design from Art Deco to postmodernism.
name: International Design Centre Nagoya
address: Japan, 〒460-0008 Aichi, Nagoya, Naka Ward, Sakae, 3 Chome−18−番1号, デザインセンタービル

detail_description: In the vibrant city of Nagoya, Japan, the World Cosplay Summit takes place in July and August. This event is a paradise for cosplay enthusiasts as it showcases participants donning intricate costumes and portraying beloved anime characters. The Osu shopping area is a popular spot for cosplayers throughout the year, but during late July to early August, the entire Sakae neighborhood becomes a hub for colorful costumes and anime-themed festivities.
name: World Cosplay Summit
address: Ark Sakae Plaza Building, 9F, 1 Chome-10-9 Higashisakura, Higashi Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 461-0005, Japan

detail_description: Nittaiji Temple Charnel House, located in Nagoya, is a Buddhist temple that was established in 1904 to commemorate the strong bond between Thailand and Japan. This distinctive temple seamlessly integrates Japanese and Thai customs, setting it apart as one of Japan's most exceptional temples. It houses sacred relics of Buddha and stands out as the only temple in Japan not affiliated with a specific sect, representing all Buddhist sects.
name: Nittaiji Temple Charnel House
address: 1 Chome Shiroyamashinmachi, Chikusa Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 464-0046, Japan

excerpt: Expansive green space with bicycle & jogging paths, picnic areas, a pond & a baseball arena.
detail_description: Meijō Park, located around Nagoya Castle, offers a vast green space with various recreational facilities such as bicycle and jogging paths, picnic areas, and a baseball arena. The park features beautiful gardens, serene walking paths, and cultural events throughout the year. Visitors can also enjoy a 660m long corridor of Wisteria from Nagoya Castle's East Gate to Meijo Park's southern gardens for free.
name: Meijō Park
address: 1 Chome-2-25 Meijo, Kita Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 462-0846, Japan

excerpt: Emblematic 180-m. steel tower with 2 observation decks & a local produce market.
detail_description: The Chubu Electric Power MIRAI TOWER, also known as the Nagoya TV Tower, is a prominent 180-meter steel structure in Nagoya's Hisaya Odori Park. It boasts two observation decks and a local produce market. Completed in 1954, it predates Tokyo Tower and offers stunning views of Nagoya and neighboring Hisaya-odori Park from its 100-meter-high observation deck.
name: Chubu Electric Power MIRAI TOWER
address: 3 Chome-6-１５先 Nishiki, Naka Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 460-0003, Japan

excerpt: Elegant retail district Osu is home to centuries-old shops for Japanese crafts, as well as modern fashion boutiques. Landmark holy sites include tranquil restored Buddhist temple Osu Kannon and Shinto shrines Kitano and Miwa. Hip pop-up restaurants and taco joints define the dining scene, and Western-style brewpubs serve Japanese craft beer. Wakamiya Odori Park is popular for strolling and jogging.
detail_description: Osu, a stylish retail area in Nagoya, is known for its mix of traditional Japanese craft shops and modern fashion boutiques. Visitors can explore historic sites like the Osu Kannon Buddhist temple and the Kitano and Miwa Shinto shrines. The district also offers a diverse dining scene with pop-up restaurants, taco joints, and Western-style brewpubs serving Japanese craft beer. Wakamiya Odori Park provides a peaceful setting for leisurely walks or jogging.
name: Osu
address: Naka Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 460-0011, Japan

excerpt: Stadium for the Chunichi Dragons baseball team seating 40,000 under an elaborate geodesic dome roof.
detail_description: Vantelin Dome Nagoya is a popular tourist attraction in Nagoya, Japan. It is the stadium for the Chunichi Dragons baseball team and can seat up to 40,000 people under an intricate geodesic dome roof. The area around the stadium offers opportunities for shopping at places like Mitsukoshi (Nagoya) for souvenirs and travel accessories.
name: Vantelin Dome Nagoya
address: 1 Chome-1-1 Daikominami, Higashi Ward, Nagoya, Aichi 461-0047, Japan

detail_description: The Antarctic Museum and Former Research Ship Fuji is a must-visit attraction in Nagoya Port. The bright orange icebreaker ship, which was active in the Antarctic for 18 years starting from 1965, is now moored as a historical display. Visitors can explore the interior of the ship, which has been transformed into an experience-style exhibition. Additionally, the Garden Pier offers an Observation Lounge, Maritime Museum, and dining facilities.
name: Antarctic Museum and Former Research Ship Fuji
address: Japan, 〒455-0033 Aichi, Nagoya, Minato Ward, Minatomachi, 1−9, 名古屋港ｶﾞｰﾃﾞﾝふ頭

detail_description: Nagoya City Agricultural Center is a sprawling park offering various attractions. Visitors can unwind on its expansive green fields, take leisurely walks amidst diverse flowers like roses and Japanese irises, and explore the greenhouse. The park provides designated areas for picnics and barbecues on sunny days. Additionally, Nagoya is a well-planned urban center known for its prosperity driven by the presence of major companies like Toyota.

excerpt: Civic building built in 1933 with a 12-story tower & a blend of Japanese and Western design.
detail_description: Nagoya City Hall, a civic building constructed in 1933, boasts a unique blend of Japanese and Western architectural styles. The 12-story tower stands as a symbol of the city's rich history and modern development. Surrounding the hall are various industrial landmarks such as Nagoya train station, port, airfield, and several museums including the SCMaglev and Railway Park Museum. Visitors can also enjoy panoramic views of the city from the 180-meter-tall Nagoya TV Tower nearby.
